defaultFor some years now
default&#xa0;
defaultWarwickshire
default&#xa0;
defaultPolice have been focusing on harm reduction and the effective management of risk and harm to citizens rather than pursuing detection performance.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe main emphasis being crime reduction, thereby stopping crime happening in the first place.
default&#xa0;
defaultOf course, the force like other force's measures detection performance for all crime types but the daily performance focus is on the dashboard.
default&#xa0;
defaultThere are 3 detection targets on the dashboard for robbery, violence with injury and burglary which are included to reflect the harm that these crimes cause within the community.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultA recent review in
default&#xa0;
defaultWarwickshire (some of which is outlined below) with regards to compliance with National Crime Recording Standards (NCRS) and Home Office Counting Rules (HOCR) has not indicated that force targets are adversely affecting crime recording
default&#xa0;
defaultpractices.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultQuestion 2default&#xa0;
defaultReview in Warwickshire and West MerciadefaultCrime Bureaudefault&#xa0;
defaultIn July 2013, following the HMIC report in Kent, ACC Morgan was requested
default&#xa0;
default to undertake a review of the crime recording processes and practices in both Forces
default&#xa0;
default and assess any 'risk' of similar issues. The work and report was submitted by the lead within the Crime Bureau, DCI Tony Love, in July and the strategic lead, ACC Morgan, summarised the report with the following comments:-
default&#xa0;
default“My assessment is that both forces operate robust oversight and compliance mechanisms that ensure adherence to HOCR and where the balance between individual decisions and oversight ensures good decision making.” default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultSince that date, there has been progress within the Crime Bureau to align and develop processes and DCI Love has refreshed his original report (July 2013). This report to the Committee highlights the key safeguards which are in place to ensure ethical crime recording is taking place and adds further strength to the comments from ACC Morgan as above.
default&#xa0;
defaultCrime Registrardefault&#xa0;
defaultOn 1st October 2013, the Crime Registrar function transferred across to Business Assurance &amp; Improvement.
default&#xa0;
default This move has provided the opportunity for the Crime Registrar to commence independent, structured audits across both forces.
default&#xa0;
default Spreadsheets have been developed and implemented outlining both methodology and evidence of the audit work to date. This work is undertaken daily and core themes identified are raised with relevant individuals.
default&#xa0;
default The Senior Detectives Forum, chaired by the Crime Manager, remains a good platform in which to raise any Home Office Counting Rule (HOCR) issues. The approach moving forward is to develop this work and initially the audits, with the resources available, will consist of daily reviews of logs on both STORM &amp; OIS.
default&#xa0;
default These audits will consist of the following:-
